elements.title: What's an element?
elements.content:
An element is a self-defined set of 3D meshes that is linked to data on one or more underlying digital twins.

A primary twin is the main digital twin counterpart for an element. You connect the element to a twin in your Azure Digital Twins instance so that the element can represent your twin and its data within the 3D visualization.

behaviors.title: What's a behavior?
behaviors.mainContent:
A behavior is a scenario for your scene that will leverage particular data on the related element's digital twin to drive viewer visualizations.

Creating a behavior includes choosing twins, configuring status and alerts, adding a widget, and choosing which layer to display on.
behaviors.statusDescription: States are data-driven overlays on your elements to indicate the health or status of the element. Set value ranges to create state boundaries, and choose colors to represent each state in the visualization.
behaviors.alertsDescription: Alerts are conditional notifications to help you quickly see when an element requires your attention. Customize your alert badge with an icon, color, and text.

twins.title: How do I choose twins?
twins.mainContent:
On the Twins tab, you can modify the set of twins whose data is available to this behavior. This includes the targeted elements' primary twins and additional twins.

An additional twin is a secondary digital twin data source for an element. You'll be able to use properties from that twin in your behavior expressions for this element. You should only add additional twins when there are twins with data beyond your primary twin that you want to leverage in your status, alerts, and widgets for this behavior.
twins.tipContent: Azure Digital Twins Explorer can help you see twins that might be related to the primary twin for this element. You can query your graph using SELECT * FROM digitaltwins WHERE $dtId='<primary-twin-id>', and then use the double-click expansion feature to explore related twins.

widgets.title: What's a widget?
widgets.mainContent: Widgets are data-driven visuals that provide additional context and data, to help you understand the scenario that the behavior represents. Configuring widgets will help you make sure the right data is discoverable when an alert or status is active.
widgets.gaugeDescription: <Underline>Gauge:</Underline> For representing numerical data points visually
widgets.linkDescription: <Underline>Link:</Underline> For including externally-referenced content via a linked URL
widgets.valueDescription: <Underline>Value:</Underline> For directly displaying twin property values

sceneLayers.title: What's a scene layer?
sceneLayers.mainContent:
You can create layers in your scene to help organize your behaviors. Layers act like tags on the behaviors, enabling you to define which behaviors need to be seen together, thus creating custom views of your scene for different roles or tasks.

If there are no layers in a scene, all of the behaviors will show up in the scene viewer. Any behaviors not tagged with a layer will appear in the Default layer until they're tagged with a layer.

One way to create layers is to use the Scene layers button in the Build view for a scene. Alternatively, you can create layers while creating or modifying a behavior.
